140 HISTORY OF THE ABIPONES.

I do not deny that the Abipones have been savage, inhuman, and ferociOUS, but only against those whom they believed to be their enemies. Before peace was established, they affficted all Paraguay, for many years, with fire, slaughter, and rapine3 but this they looked upon as the privilege of war, and indeed a thing to be gloried in, because they always found or sus- pected the Spaniards their enemieS. They thought they were only repelling force by force, and returning inj uries for injuries, slaughters for slaughters 3 which they deny to be wrong or dis- honourable3 seeing the same so frequently done, in time of war, by the Spaniards to the Portu- gueze, and by the Portugueze to the Spaniards. Led by their example, they insisted upon it that they should not be called assassins, and thieveS‚ but soldiers, whose duty it is to offend their adversaries, and defend themselves and their possessions to the utmost of their power. The heads of the Spaniards severed from their shoulders, they called their trophies, and pre- served as testimonials of their valour. The innu- merable herds of cattle, the thousands ofhorseS, in short whatever they took from the Spaniards, they called booty justly obtained in war.
